	"\s[1]Oh, dear. Yes, I realize the word is somewhat strange; it confused me when I was learning Common, too...\n \s[0]'Card' is the proper descriptor for any person of \_a[OnWhatSuits]the four Suits\_a. \s[1]Essentially, it just... means the same as 'person.' I'm a Card, you're\w3 a Card\w9.\w9.\w9.\f[height,-2]\s[0] I think\w9.\w9.\w9.\f[height,default]\n Er, it's just a more formal word than 'person,' I suppose -- plus, it gets rid of any specificity of referring to one's Suit; rather than specifying I am a Diamond every time you speak of me,\s[1] you could instead \f[italic,1]shroud me in mystery\f[italic,default] and simply label me a 'Card.'\w3\s[0] On that note, if someone refers to 'Cards,'\w2 it's simply a more formal and respectful way of addressing a group of people, whether it consists of folks of differing Suits or not.\n\n\w6\s[1]\f[height,-2]Let's see, what do I remember about it from my classes... \s[3]I should know these things; I'm a translator, damnit...\f[height,default]\s[0] i-\w2it's capitalized to show respect,\w2 and,\w4 er...\n\n \w9\s[1]...I'm very sorry. The rules surrounding it are a bit vague; Common is a strange language.\s[0]\n\w8Some, like myself, just say it out of habit, ha! \s[1]We don't even know why... it is simply the 'proper' word you're taught in school -- always refer to your elders and superiors as such, et cetera... \s[0]\w4I think that's rather silly, though.\n\_w[1000] \s[1]...You may refer to \f[italic,1]me\f[italic,default] however you please. \w9\w9"
	--
