FunFact : nonoverlap_pool
{
	"I will tell you about my favourite native Kosani animal, the Kikuminu! It is a fluffy little thing... they are native to the Ani'ana Prefecture of Kosanu, but are also a common pet throughout the landmass. They are quadrupedal, with huge ears on the tops of their heads, ha!\n Diamonds and Kikuminu share many attributes -- Kikuminu, too, have bushy tails and small paws. However, they only have two eyes -- poor little things. I wonder how they see!\n\n Kikuminu are colourblind -- though, I suppose that doesn't matter much, being native to an environment with primarily white and blue... ehehe!\n Their sense of smell is extremely acute, as well as their hearing -- another attribute we share.\n\n They are omnivores, but prefer a meaty diet... wild Kikuminu have very sharp teeth to hunt prey, while more domesticated lines have tended towards duller, slightly shorter teeth. There exist a few coat variations in both colour and length, but most are a pale white... as well as extremely fluffy, ehehe.\n\n They are semi-aquatic; in their natural state, they spend about 40% of their time in the water, hunting aquatic prey and... well, seemingly just swimming around for the hell of it.\n\n They're very cute... the lady who owns the fish market over in Okkai has a really friendly one, you should ask to pet it sometime!"
	
	"I'll tell you about a common livestock animal native to Kosanu: the Sunnai. You've probably seen them... my neighbors have a huge flock of them, you'd have to pass their pasture every time you come here from town. They're the big, fat wooly things that flop around...\w9\w9 yes, yes, the ones with the big curly horns! Those are domestic Sunnai, omnivorous semi-aquatic animals native to the Shui'o Nui and Ani'ana Prefectures of Kosanu.\n\n Thousands of years ago, our ancestors hunted wild Sunnai for their horns. These horns were made into the hilts of weapons, since they're curved to the perfect contour of the hand, very nice to hold... I happen to have a sword fashioned with a Sunnai horn as the hilt, haha.\n The Sunnai were also hunted for their fatty blubber, to make candles as well as to use as a base for soups.\n\n Wild Sunnai are very aggressive, which led to the death of many hunters at the time; eventually, however, some brave soul learned...\w9\w6 somehow...\w9\w6 that you can actually milk them!\w5 And on top of that, they learned that the milk was \f[italic,true]absolutely delicious\f[italic,false]. This made people start to realize, 'ah, maybe we should domesticate these animals,' something that was... easier said than done, to say the least.\n Starting somewhere around a thousand years ago, the Sunnai were finally able to be wrangled, and slowly became less aggressive as they warmed up to Cards. Today, some are raised for their milk, but others are raised to output as much blubber as possible -- if you ever see a pasture full of absolutely \f[italic,true]rotund\f[italic,false] Sunnai, they are most likely being bred specifically for their blubber, ha!\n The horns are harvested at death, and are now used to make tools and such...\n\n The wild Sunnai population has also recovered very well. You can find a great lot of them if you travel up to the coast of Shui'o Nui Prefecture in the Selyr... if you go at the very beginning of Moonfall, you may be able to witness the herds all gathering for their migration southeast to Quatangu Loch. Truly, an amazing sight... just don't let them spot you, ha! The wild ones are still a bit mean...\n\n If you ever get the chance to try blubber-base stew, you should! It is very tasty, and it goes great in a nice, crispy bread bowl... truly divine."
	
	"Ooh, I have a good one... I'll teach you about one of my favourite snacks, the Clarenchetti biscuit.\n \s[0]Back about three hundred years ago, in the Seventeenth Age, a famous Scavve confectioner was visiting the city of Iy, Lacerta. Iy is famous for its spicy foods, so the sweet-toothed confectioner was having a difficult time getting through each meal... his husband -- a Heart, for context -- laughed at him, telling him that he should stick to milder foods. The confectioner took this as a challenge, of course, and started thinking of ways he could prove his beloved wrong... \n He took some of the leftovers back to the inn they were staying at, and asked to use their kitchen -- they obliged, as his reputation preceded him. By mixing a sugary concoction with the spicy pepper paste from his previous meal, he created a sweet-and-spicy coulis -- er, that's a fancy word for 'fruit sauce' -- and sandwiched it neatly between two biscuits. A craze was born; people couldn't stop mixing sweet and spicy! Many new and interesting Scavve-Iyal fusion dishes were created during this time, such as sweet noodles -- which, yes, we Diamonds discovered hundreds of years before them... but the Iyal version tastes quite different, so I can't blame them for taking credit, ehehe! \n\n The snack is traditionally stamped with a mixed Heart and Spade symbol. This represents the confectioner and his husband's relationship, which sparked the ordeal... so cute!"
	
	{
		"Hehe, since you are not Kosani, perhaps I can finally find a use for all these trivial facts about Diamond biology...\n Did you know that these little antennae on my head are actually prehensile? Yes, yes... er, I won't demonstrate, as mine are quite frail -- I'm old, after all... but! They can move around, and the tips can even bend to hold things..!\n They were more useful when we lived underground; in the rare event of the cave being too dark, our ancestors grasped small torches with their antennae, leaving their hands free to climb or carry things.\n\n As time has gone on, and as we exercised our little 'head hands' less, they have... evolved backwards, so to speak. Adapted their way out of being useful... now we mostly just put jewelry on them! Still, I think it's an interesting little feature.\n ...And, if you're around folks who aren't aware they can move, you can freak them out a bit by wiggling the antennae around. \s[1]Always a fun thing to do at parties, when it's in need of a bit of chaos... ehehe."
	
		if Flag("underground") == 0; MiscFlags ,= "underground"
	}
	
	{
		"Ah, did you know that Diamonds' eyes are especially sensitive to light?\w6 Yes, hehe... we can see quite well in the dark because of it. A Spade friend of mine visited the shrine recently, and asked why I keep it so dimly lit... it surprised me, because I was about to complain about the room being too bright, haha!\n\n Our sensitivity to light seems to surprise some people, since we live in bright, shining snow... indeed, snow blindness is an issue we face quite a bit. Thankfully, however, we have masks and special glasses we can wear if we plan on being outside for long periods of time... some are even quite stylish.\n Personally, I dislike them... not too comfortable, in my opinion. I prefer the more archaic option; our ancestors created hooded cloaks with sheer dark veils, like curtains for your face! They're a lot cozier than the glasses, some even have pretty designs... lace veils, for example. Very fashionable.\n\n We evolved to have good night vision because, "
			--
			if Flag("underground") == 0; "long ago, "
			else; "as you know, "
			--
		"we actually dwelled far underground, in cozy little caves. We came out onto the surface only at night, to hunt and harvest crops. Unfortunately, an earthquake caused the population to migrate outdoors about three thousand years ago... because the earthquakes have continued, we have been surface-dwellers ever since.\n Perhaps some day, the quakes will cease, and we will retreat underground again... I doubt it, though. Life is much easier on the surface."
		
		if Flag("underground") == 0; MiscFlags ,= "underground"
	}
}

